  <h1>Diminished Value Claims</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>What is diminished value?</h2><p>After a vehicle is repaired following an accident, it is worth less on the market than an identical vehicle with no accident history. This reduction in value — diminished value (DV) — is a recoverable damage from the at-fault driver&rsquo;s insurer in most states.</p>
  <h2>The 17c formula</h2><p>Georgia&rsquo;s State Farm formula, widely used: DV = 10% × ACV × damage multiplier × mileage multiplier. Damage multiplier: 1.0 (structural/severe), 0.75 (major), 0.50 (moderate), 0.25 (minor/superficial). Mileage multiplier: 1.0 (&lt;20K miles), 0.80 (20–40K), 0.60 (40–60K), 0.40 (60–80K), 0.20 (80–100K), 0 (&gt;100K).</p>
  <h2>First-party vs. third-party DV</h2><p>Third-party DV (from the at-fault driver&rsquo;s insurer): available in most states. First-party DV (from your own insurer): most policies explicitly exclude it. A few states (Georgia, Florida) require first-party DV coverage.</p>
  <h2>Documenting your DV claim</h2><p>Get an independent appraisal from a certified appraiser familiar with DV claims. Submit the 17c calculation alongside the appraisal. Dealers and private party listings for comparable vehicles before and after the accident strengthen the claim.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-property-damage-claims-work">how claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
